IV. Sex Determination TTYP
A. Klinefelter’s syndrome-XXY (1/500 males)
1. Small testes, no spermatozoa-infertile
2. Male secondary traits-normal
3. Mental retardation
4. Gynecomastia-breast enlargement due to estrogen
5. Tall stature-longer legs

B. Turner’s syndrome-XO (1/3000) females —prenatal incidence perhaps 2%—few survive
1. Ovary begins to develop then atrophies-streak ovary
2. Female secondary traits-immature
3. Amenorrhea-failure of menarche by age 16

C. Androgen insensitivity—XY females
1. Loss of function in testosterone receptor
2. Male gonad-undescended testes
3. Female secondary traits

D. 5 a-ketosteroid reductase 2 deficiency—XY
1. Reduced levels of dihydrotestosterone
2. Internal anatomy is male-testosterone
a. Wolffian duct retained, loss of Müllerian duct
3. External anatomy is female-low DHT until puberty
a. Masculinization at puberty when testosterone levels increase

